why: Primary baseline: Table 1 Col 1 effort ~ wage + limited + limitedwage with subject FE and cluster SE. Coefficient 2.731.
No wage controls -- just limited dummy with subject FE. Tests whether wage controls matter for limited effect.
Table 1 Col 2: adds requestedeffort + period dummies. Published robustness from the paper itself.
Wage + limited without interaction term. Tests whether restricting the functional form matters.
Adds offered share as control. Tests whether the offered share confounds the limited effect.
Adds period dummies to baseline. Tests whether time trends drive the result.
Table A1: adds wage^2 and limited*wage^2. Published appendix robustness for nonlinear wage effects.
Adds requested effort only (no period dummies). Subset of Table 1 Col 2 controls.
Wage bins instead of continuous wage. Tests functional form of wage control.
Log wage instead of level. Alternative functional form for wage control.
All available controls (wage + wage^2 + limitedwage + limitedwage^2 + requestedeffort + share + period dummies).
Only the limited*wage interaction -- drops the limited main effect. Changes the treatment variable interpretation entirely.
Wage + share + requested effort as controls. Combined control set.
First half periods (1-7). Tests whether effect is present early in the experiment.
Second half periods (8-15). Tests whether effect persists in later rounds.
Exclude period 1 (learning). Removes potential learning effects in first round.
Exclude period 15 (end-game). Removes potential end-game effects in final round.
Exclude periods 1 and 15. Removes both learning and end-game effects.
Low wage contracts only (wage<10). Tests effect at low wages where limited contracts should matter most.
Medium/high wage only (wage>=10). Tests effect at higher wages.
High wage only (wage>=20). Tests effect at highest wages -- result becomes insignificant (p=0.19) suggesting the effect is concentrated at lower wages as the theory predicts.
Matching group 1 only. Tests stability across matching groups.
Matching group 2 only. Tests stability across matching groups.
Drop corner efforts (0 and 10). Removes boundary effects from the 0-10 effort scale.
Sessions with base treatment first (400-600). Exact duplicate of baseline -- all base treatment observations come from these sessions.
Drop session 400. Leave-one-session-out robustness.
Drop session 500. Leave-one-session-out robustness.
Drop session 600. Leave-one-session-out robustness.
Table 1 Col 3: principal profit as outcome. Different dependent variable testing a related but distinct claim about employer surplus.
Agent profit as outcome (all contracts incl. rejected). Different dependent variable.
Agent profit as outcome (accepted only). Different dependent variable -- note coefficient is -2.731 (exact negative of baseline) because agent profit = wage - effort mechanically.
Log effort as outcome. Different transformation of the dependent variable.
Binary high effort indicator (effort >= median). Different dependent variable testing extensive margin of effort.
Effort minus requested effort as outcome. Tests voluntary compliance above the minimum.
Acceptance decision as outcome. Different dependent variable testing whether employees accept limited contracts less often.
Total surplus (principal + agent profit) as outcome. Different dependent variable testing efficiency.
Screening treatment (treatmentid==1) instead of base. Different experimental treatment arm with reputation/competition -- tests a distinct claim.
Screening treatment with reputation controls (Table 2 Col 2). Different treatment arm with additional controls for reputation effects.
Pool base and screening treatments. Mixes two different treatment arms.
Base second treatment (treatmentid==2). Subjects who played screening first then base -- potential order effects.
Screen second treatment (treatmentid==4). Subjects who played base first then screening -- limited effect is insignificant (p=0.10).
Robust SE (heteroskedasticity-robust without clustering). Same point estimate as baseline (2.731) with smaller SE (0.348).
Classical (IID) SE. Same point estimate with slightly smaller SE (0.378).
Cluster by session. Same point estimate with much smaller SE (0.201) -- only 3 clusters so likely too narrow.
Cluster by session x matching group. Same point estimate with SE 0.338.
CRV1 clustered by subject (baseline inference). Exact duplicate of baseline SE computation.
OLS with subject dummies + cluster by subject. Manual FE implementation via statsmodels -- same point estimate.
Pooled OLS with HC3 SE. Different point estimate (2.386) because it drops subject FE.
Pooled OLS without subject FE. Tests importance of within-subject identification.
Random effects estimator. Close to FE (2.658 vs 2.731) suggesting FE assumption is appropriate.
First differences. Coefficient 2.595 is close to baseline confirming within-subject result.
Between estimator (subject means). Insignificant (p=0.36) with wrong sign -- confirms the effect is within-subject not cross-sectional.
Ordered probit treating effort as ordinal. Insignificant (p=0.77) -- structural model mismatch since the ordered probit does not account for subject FE.
FE regression on interior efforts only (2-9). Removes boundary observations to test truncation effects.
Log effort on level wage. Same as outcome/log_effort -- duplicate with different spec_id.
Level effort on log wage. Alternative functional form for the wage variable.
Cubic in wage. Higher-order polynomial for wage variable.
Standardized wage. Coefficient rescaled but same regression -- tests interpretability not robustness.
Weighted by inverse subject observation count (pooled OLS). Balances across subjects with different numbers of accepted contracts.
Weighted by period/15 (later periods weighted more). Upweights experienced play.
Placebo: randomly scramble limited assignment across all observations. Coefficient near zero (-0.002 p=0.99) confirming real assignment matters.
Placebo: lagged effort on current contract type. Insignificant (p=0.43) -- current contract type does not predict past effort.
Placebo: does limited predict next period wage? Insignificant (p=0.40) -- no reverse causality from contract type to future wages.
Period 1 only (pooled OLS no FE). Insignificant (p=0.49) -- with only one observation per subject FE is impossible and cross-sectional variation is weak.
Placebo: within-subject permutation of contract type. Small coefficient (0.60 p=0.02) -- some residual correlation due to within-subject sorting patterns.
Heterogeneity by session order (base first vs screen first). Tests whether order of treatment arms matters.
Heterogeneity by matching group. Tests stability across experimental groups.
Heterogeneity: limited x late period interaction. Tests whether effect changes over time.
Heterogeneity: limited x high wage interaction. Tests whether effect varies by wage level.
Heterogeneity: limited x high requested effort. Tests whether effect varies by employer's requested effort.
Screening: full reputation interactions (Table 2 Col 4). Different treatment arm with reputation heterogeneity.
Screening treatment low reputation agents only. Subsample of different treatment arm.
Screening treatment medium/high reputation agents only. Subsample of different treatment arm.
Triple difference: limited x screening treatment. Tests differential effect of limited in screening vs base.
Heterogeneity: limited x generous share. Tests whether effect varies by how generously the employer splits surplus.
Profit with subject FE + cluster SE. Different dependent variable (employer profit) with panel FE.
Profit with quadratic wage (Table A1). Different dependent variable with nonlinear wage.
Profit with period dummies. Different dependent variable with time controls.
Screening treatment full controls (Table 2 Col 5). Different treatment arm (screening) with full set of controls.
Median regression (no FE). Tests whether the conditional median response is similar to conditional mean.
Q25 regression (no FE). Tests effect at lower end of effort distribution.
Q75 regression (no FE). Tests effect at upper end of effort distribution.
Middle periods (5-10). Tests effect in interior of the experiment.
Drop zero employee surplus observations (wage != requestedeffort). Removes cases where employee gets nothing extra.
Session x Period FE instead of subject FE. Different FE structure absorbing session-time variation.
Two-way FE: subject + period. Adds period FE to baseline subject FE.
Matching group FE only. Coarser FE than subject -- tests between-subject variation within groups.
Probit for acceptance decision. Different dependent variable (acceptance) and different estimation method.
